{
  "texts": [
    "These paradigms have therefore intrinsically confounded both error types.Prediction error to unexpected absence has been investigated mainly through the so-called omission paradigm (see [21] for a review), where a periodically presented standard stimulus is occasionally replaced by silence (i.e., an omission).",
    "The omission responses evoked in this paradigm are often interpreted as prediction errors [21][22][23].",
    "However, these studies did not consider a theoretical distinction between feature and absence representations and did not manipulate listeners' beliefs about the probability of presence of the stimuli.",
    "Consequently, it remains unclear whether omission responses reflect prediction error or instead result from neural entrainment to the periodic presentation of stimuli [18,24,25].In this preregistered study [26] we used a novel experimental design to test whether the sensory pathway encodes absence prediction error (Hypothesis 1) and to determine whether it is represented within the same circuits where feature prediction error was previously reported.",
    "We chose the auditory pathway as a model system because there is strong evidence that feature prediction error is expressed along the ascending hierarchy [13,27,28]."
  ]
}